3.0.0 Investigating AutoML

3.1.0 Choosing a Focus Area

When undertaking a project such as this on a topic as broad as machine learning it is essential to focus on a particular subsection to create the best possible work. In this instance, my focus was to be on a time series model in the context of event recognition such as gesture recognition or audio classification within a stream of data. While searching through the fastAi forum: https://forums.fast.ai/ , it became quite clear that image-based models were quite common whereas audio was still quite a scarce topic within the main fastAi library thus making it the appropriate choice for a project such as this.

3.2.0 How the Model Works.

3.2.1 How it works

When researching pre-existing state of the art models from which to base my project on, I began by searching through the papers with code site to identify any projects that could be beneficial, ( https://paperswithcode.com/ ).

Whilst searching, I noticed references to the librosa python library ( https://librosa.org/doc/latest/index.html ), an audio and music analysis platform within python. A key function within the library that stood out to me was the melSpectrogram conversion, a function that takes an audio file and returns an image spectrogram in its place.

Source: https://librosa.org/doc/latest/generated/librosa.feature.melspectrogram.html?highlight=spectrogram#librosa.feature.melspectrogram

Whilst no specific models existed for audio training, there was a plethora of image-based models that use the CNN learner, therefore I began to consider the possibility of taking an audio dataset and converting it to a series of spectrogram images.

I found a programme to carry out this conversion on Kaggle by using the ‘freesound audio tagging 2019’ dataset. The programme loops through a directory taking all the relevant files, converting them, and resaving them in a new directory for future use. The programme can be accessed here:

https://www.kaggle.com/rftexas/converting-sounds-into-images-a-general-guide

Whilst the programme exists outside of Google Colab, it proves that the theory behind the model is practically feasible and can be implemented, meaning that in order to classify an audio sample, you must convert it to a spectrogram image and pass it through a CNN.

3.2.2 FastAudio

While continuing to search for audio classification models that were implemented in association with fastAi, I came across the fastAudio module that is designed to work in association with fastAi.

The library is available from the following git repository and is extensively documented below:

GIT: https://github.com/fastaudio/fastaudio

DOC: https://fastaudio.github.io/

Within this module, the transformation to convert a tensor of audio files to MelSpectrograms is built in, allowing the user to take advantage of the processing potential of the GPU. Furthermore, the module creates an ‘AudioBlock’, for the DataBlock API, meaning that an audio file can be passed when running predictions on an exported model which wouldn’t of been possible within the standard fastAi library.

The fastAudio repository also contains a working sample model which is trained on the Environmental Sound Classification data set. This formed the basis for the generalised model I went on the create which is discussed here (<model html link>). The sample model can be accessed here: https://github.com/fastaudio/fastaudio/blob/master/docs/ESC50:%20Environmental%20Sound%20Classification.ipynb

3.3.0 Implementing the Model

3.3.1 Reworking an Existing Model

Due to the lack of standardised labelling within datasets, there is a risk that a model will only run for one unique dataset, which is not ideal for this project. Therefore, before continuing any further with adjusting the model I aimed to have it run as it is, but on a separate data set.

Using the steps in section 2.2.3, I downloaded the cat and dog dataset from Kaggle available here: https://www.kaggle.com/mmoreaux/audio-cats-and-dogs .

The requirements of the system require the labels to come from a csv column, with another column containing the filename. I was able to manually adjust the file in excel to carry this out.

Source original: https://www.kaggle.com/mmoreaux/audio-cats-and-dogs?select=train_test_split.csv

Within the original model, the only transformation required was the audio to melSpectrogram function. However, the ESC50 dataset uses files of similar lengths which satisfies the requirements of the learner. This isn’t always the case therefore each file needs to be truncated/padded to a certain length using the following function:

This restricts the size of the audio to sample to 1000ms, or the length of whatever parameter is passed.

The original model was also reliant on a crossValidationSplitter that was specific to the original dataset. I substituted his for the random TrainTestSplitter as this removed any potential biased and ensure that the model was appropriately changed without being influenced by the dataset.

Beyond this, the model trains successfully, however, the accuracy isn’t quite as high as I would of preferred for such a relatively simple system (80%). Therefore I used the learning rate finder built-in to the fastAi library and was able to use this to fine tune the model to approximately 96% accuracy, a significant improvement on the original training cycle.

The learning rate finder within fastAi operates by taking several mini batches, starting with an incredibly small learning rate and then measuring the loss. It does this repeatedly, increasing the learning rate by a fixed percentage each time, accumulating the associated losses with each learning rate, This is then returned to the user in the form of a curve which can be displayed within the Colab platform. An example of such a curve:

Source: https://colab.research.google.com/github/fastai/fastbook/blob/master/05_pet_breeds.ipynb#scrollTo=VymuqdZcQRsi

All code samples shown throughout this second have been taken from the reworked version of the ESC50 model and have been published at the following git repository: https://github.com/kmcshane811/AutoML/blob/main/Cat_%26_Dog_Audio_Classification.ipynb .

All modifications and publication of the code are done under The MIT license with all rights going to the owner. https://github.com/fastaudio/fastaudio/blob/master/LICENSE.txt

3.3.2 Creating a General Model Programme

After verifying the feasibility of applying other datasets to a model, it becomes permissible to begin working on a range of datasets. The first step in implementing such a system is too first remove all instances of absolute file paths, providing the system the ability to operate with any file regardless of it’s name.

Using the fastAi Path() class, the base directory of the system is stored within the identifier path.

Firstly, using the path.ls(file_exts = ‘…’) function, it is possible to return all the files containing the .csv file extension as an array to find the meta data of the dataset. Then, by casting the value to a string, it can be appended to the ‘/content/’ file extension, which is the base directory for google colab.

Once the file path has been declared, the data frame can be declared as normal, replacing the absolute file path with the variable ‘csv_path’.

Secondly, using a user input, the system identifies the file containing the data to be used for testing and training. The model is not designed to work with separate test and training files therefore all data should be treated equally and stored within a single directory. It was noted that within some datasets, the file path is included within the csv file containing the metadata. To deal with such an issue, if the user leaves the input blank, the default value is ‘/content/’, meaning the data can still be read.

Finally, in a bid to avoid defining strict rules on naming conventions within the csv file, the system was designed to allow the user to enter the column names which contained the independent and dependent variables, which can then be used within the data block which shall be displayed below.

To cement the changes made when preparing the data frame, several small but significant changes are required within the Data Block in order to ensure the code runs as intended.

Firstly, within the get_x parameters, the parameters of ColReader should be changed to the variable x and the prefix to the file variable. It is essential to note that this function will not concatenate a variable (i.e x) and an absolute file path in the pref (i.e pref = ‘/content/set_a/’), both values must be a variable in order too ensure the code runs.

Then, similarly to the get_x requirements, it is necessary to change the string value in get_y to the variable y to again allow for flexibility between datasets.

As before, this code was based on the ESC50 audio classification model and is available to view and access at the following Github repository:

https://github.com/kmcshane811/AutoML/blob/main/Generalised_Audio_Classification.ipynb

3.3.3 Creating a General Prediction Model

The aim of the prediction model is to allow the user to upload an exported pkl file of a model and a range of data and have the model run predictions on it. As with the training model discussed previously, this programme was designed with flexibility and the ability to run with a range of data type of models at heart

Once the user uploads the relevant data files and the model, the following is implemented to build the necessary file paths.

As before, the Path() class is invoked to generate the base directory path and the user is then asked to state the file extension of the data they are using. This minor interaction broadens the possibilities of the system as, rather than being limited to a singular file type, it can be used for a range of audio and visual files thus making it applicable in multiple fields.

The path.ls(file_exts=’…’) function is once again invoked to create an array containing the model file path and the file path of the data files uploaded for predictions.

Finally, the learner is loaded with the uploaded model, allowing it to begin operating without the use of the train function from the previous programme.

Once the learner has been initialised, a for loop is called to carry out predictions on multiple files within a single execution, removing the need for the user to manually upload files for each prediction.

The loop converts each individual file into an audio tensor which is passed into the learner. The learner in turn, takes the file and returns the label it has predicted it as and the percentage certainty of the model in it’s predictions.

3.3.4 Creating a Tabular Model

Audio is stored digitally on devices as a series of discrete values at different time intervals, meaning that it contains a series of extractable features that can be represented in a tabular format and consequently analysed. When creating this model I used the CNN classifier as a base template to enable the generalised access to the meta data and source file for the dataset.

After defining the pandas data frame of the meta data, the system goes on too create a new csv file containing all the extracted data of the audio data as follows:

source: https://github.com/kmcshane811/AutoML/blob/main/Generalised_Tabular_Audio_Classification.ipynb

Using the librosa audio manipulation package within python the following data can be extracted:

Chroma_stft: A chromagram feature represent of the 12 pitch levels;

Rmse: The root-mean-square energy of the frames within the audio sample;

Spectral centroid: A measure used in digital audio sampling to define a spectrum and identify the spectrum’s centre of mass;

Spectral Bandwidth: The spectral bandwidth is defined as the band width of light at one-half the peak maximum;

Roll off: The frequency below which a specified percentage of the total spectral energy, e.g. 85%, lies;

Zero Crossing Rate: A measure of number of times in each time interval/frame that the amplitude of the speech signals passes through a value of zero;

Mel Frequency Cepstral Coefficients (MFCCs): a small set of features (usually about 10-20) which concisely describe the overall shape of a spectral envelope.

Once the dataset has been generated, we can then initialise it as a pandas dataframe like so:

source: https://github.com/kmcshane811/AutoML/blob/main/Generalised_Tabular_Audio_Classification.ipynb

I found that conversion method generates a series of run off values that populate the first row of the file incompletely. This will result in errors due to incorrect data types being assigned, but, as this occurred across multiple datasets in the same format, I used the ‘df_nn.iloc[1:]’ function to remove the initial row from the data set, preventing any errors.

Normally, tabular data sets are reliant on a dependent variable, a set of continuous variables and a set of categorical variables. In this instance, however, there are no categorical variables worth analysing, only the dependent variable and the continuous extracted variables, for this reason only the continuous variables are passed in the data block.

source: https://github.com/kmcshane811/AutoML/blob/main/Generalised_Tabular_Audio_Classification.ipynb

When defining a tabular model, it is important to be aware of what you are trying to achieve. In regression models that are focused on trends and predictions, the dataset should be split by dates, meaning it is trained on older data and then tested against more recent data to analyse its prediction accuracy. Furthermore, the loss function employed should be root mean square error as it can be used to measure the variance of the data.

For classification models such as this, the data can be randomly separated to prevent any bias from the dataset. The learner should also employ the cross-entropy loss function in order to suitably analyse and recognise the data associated with different labels.
